1️⃣ LOGICAL REASONING – PUZZLES (SEATING ARRANGEMENT BASICS)

This is one of the most important and high-weightage topics in placements 🔥

🔹 A. TYPES OF SEATING ARRANGEMENT

1️⃣ Linear (in a row)
2️⃣ Circular (around table)
3️⃣ Facing same direction / opposite direction

🔹 B. BASIC RULES

👉 Always:

Draw diagram
Place fixed positions first
Follow clues step by step
🔹 C. LINEAR ARRANGEMENT (BASIC)
🔹 Example 1

5 people: A, B, C, D, E

Conditions:

A is at left end
B is right of A
C is at right end

Arrange:

A → B → _ → _ → C

Remaining: D, E fill middle

🔹 D. CIRCULAR ARRANGEMENT

👉 Formula idea: positions matter relative to each other

🔹 Example 2

4 people sit around a table

Fix one person (to avoid rotation confusion)

Then arrange others clockwise

🔹 E. FACING DIRECTION (IMPORTANT)

👉 If facing North → left is your left
👉 If facing South → left becomes right

🔹 Example 3

A sits facing North
B is to the right of A

👉 B is on A’s right side (East)

🔹 F. COMMON TRICKS

1️⃣ Fix one person in circular puzzles
2️⃣ Use symbols instead of names
3️⃣ Solve step-by-step (don’t jump)

📝 PRACTICE QUESTIONS
4 people sit in a row. A is left of B, C is right of B. Who is in middle?
A sits at one end, B next to A. Who can be at other end?
In a circle, A sits next to B. Where can C sit?
A faces North, B is to his right. What is B’s direction?
5 people sit in row, C is in middle. How many positions possible for others?
